# Rule: Next.js SSR Memory Guardrails

Applies to Next.js server-rendered code, including API routes, middleware, and Server Components.

## 1) Global Scope Pollution

- Prohibit `global.xxx` caching/state across requests unless intentionally implementing a singleton (for example a DB connection pool).
- Do not use mutable global state for request data.

## 2) Resource Connection Lifecycle

- Ensure DB connections, file streams, and network resources are closed, released, or returned to pools when request work completes.
- Do not leave open handles after the response path finishes.

## 3) Third-Party Leak Prevention

- Audit heavy Node.js libraries and avoid creating new heavy instances on every request.
- Reuse safe singleton/module-scope clients where appropriate.

## 4) Closure Memory Bloat

- Do not capture full request/response objects in deep closures.
- Extract only required properties before passing data to utilities.

```ts
const { userId, traceId } = requestContext;
return handleServerTask({ userId, traceId });
```
